</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">The spectrum of causes of hepatic gas detected at computed tomography (CT) and ultrasonography (US) is widening. There are many iatrogenic and noniatrogenic causes of hepatic parenchymal, biliary, hepatic venous, and portal venous gas. Hepatic gas may be an indicator of serious acute disease (infarct, infection, abscess, bowel inflammation, or trauma). In other clinical scenarios, it may be an expected finding related to therapeutic interventions (such as surgery; hepatic artery embolization for a tumor or for active bleeding in acute trauma cases; percutaneous tumor ablation performed with radiofrequency, cryotherapy, laser photocoagulation, or ethanol). In some cases, hepatic gas is an incidental finding of no clinical significance. Familiarity with the expanding list of newer intervention-related causes of hepatic gas detected at CT and US, knowledge of the patient's clinical history, and a careful search for associated clues on images are all factors that may allow the radiologist to better determine the clinical relevance of this finding.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2011</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.315095108">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.315095108">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig01a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1140" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig01a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig01b.jpeg" height="1271" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig01b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig02a.jpeg" height="1024" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig02a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig02b.jpeg" height="1008" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig02b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig02c.jpeg" height="1014" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig02c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig03a.jpeg" height="870" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig03a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig03b.jpeg" height="998" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig03b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig04.jpeg" height="1197" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig04" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span> Pneumobilia in a liver transplant recipient with an anastomotic stricture of the common bile duct. CT image shows centrally located pneumobilia (arrows) and intrahepatic ductal dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig04">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig05a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1211" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig05a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig05b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1057" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig05b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig06.jpeg" height="1195" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig06" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span> Hepatic artery embolization for trauma. CT image obtained after selective right hepatic arterial embolization with gelatin sponge for a grade 4 hepatic laceration shows multiple foci of gas (arrow). Aspiration demonstrated a sterile hematoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig06">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig07.jpeg" height="1266" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig07" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span> Radiofrequency ablation of a rectal cancer metastasis in the left hepatic lobe. CT image obtained 3 days after the procedure shows intratumoral gas (arrow). The patient was asymptomatic. The perihepatic fluid and gas (arrowhead) were related to the intraoperative technique.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig07">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig08.jpeg" height="1252" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig08" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> Ethanol chemoablation of a hepatocellular carcinoma. CT image shows a region of low attenuation (arrow) in the tumor bed. The low-attenuation region represents the zone of ethanol chemoablation from the percutaneous injection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig08">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig09a.jpeg" height="1259" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig09a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig09b.jpeg" height="1040" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig09b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig10.jpeg" height="994" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span> Hepatic gas after transjugular liver biopsy in a patient with recently elevated liver function test results. US image shows incidentally detected hepatic venous gas (arrows). Coagulopathy during treatment for leukemia prohibited use of a percutaneous approach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig11a.jpeg" height="982" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig11b.jpeg" height="1000" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig12a.jpeg" height="1058" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig12b.jpeg" height="1042" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.315095108/asset/images/095108fig13.jpeg" height="1280" width="1255" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span> Postoperative packing with oxidized cellulose. CT image shows gas (arrows) in the interstices of oxidized cellulose packing material. This appearance is typically seen within a hematoma and may mimic an abscess.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.315095108&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Liebman PR, Patten MT, Manny J, Benfield JR, Hechtman HB. Hepatic-po